---
import SchemaLayout from '../../../layouts/SchemaLayout.astro';
import drugsData from '../../../../data/drugs.json';

const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL;
const slug = 'cytotoxics';
const displayName = 'Cytotoxics';

const drugs = (drugsData as any[]).filter(
  (d: any) => (d.therapeutic_classes || []).includes(slug)
);
const drugCount = drugs.length;
---
<SchemaLayout title="Cytotoxics" schema="therapeutic-classes" description="Cytotoxic chemotherapy agents that target rapidly dividing cells through DNA damage, antimetabolite activity, and mitotic disruption">

  <div class="mb-6">
    <div class="breadcrumbs text-sm mb-4">
      <ul>
        <li><a href={`${base}schemas/02-therapeutic-classes/`} class="link">Therapeutic Classes</a></li>
        <li>{displayName}</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
    <h1 class="text-4xl font-serif font-bold text-base-content mb-2">{displayName}</h1>
    <p class="text-base-content/70 text-lg">{drugCount} drug{drugCount !== 1 ? 's' : ''} in this class</p>
  </div>

  <div class="prose max-w-none mb-10">
    <p>Cytotoxic chemotherapy agents exploit the heightened proliferative rate of malignant cells—and their resulting dependency on intact DNA replication, transcription, and mitotic machinery—to achieve selective toxicity over normal tissues, albeit with a narrower therapeutic index than any other drug class. The modern chemotherapy era began with the clinical use of nitrogen mustards in the treatment of lymphoma in the 1940s, derived from chemical warfare agents used in World War I, and expanded through systematic empirical screening programs at the National Cancer Institute to include dozens of agents active across diverse tumor types. The fundamental mechanistic categories of cytotoxic agents are DNA alkylation (nitrogen mustards, platinum compounds, nitrosoureas, alkyl sulfonates), antimetabolites (antifolates, pyrimidine analogs, purine analogs), topoisomerase inhibitors (anthracyclines for topoisomerase II, camptothecins for topoisomerase I), mitotic spindle poisons (vinca alkaloids, taxanes), and antibiotics with cytotoxic properties (bleomycin, actinomycin D, mitomycin C). The selection among these agents in clinical practice is guided by tumor histology, molecular markers, patient performance status, organ function, and the cumulative toxicity burden of prior therapy.</p>
    <p>The molecular mechanisms of cytotoxic agents, while sharing the common endpoint of DNA damage or mitotic arrest, differ substantially in their precise points of attack. Alkylating agents form covalent cross-links within DNA strands (intrastrand) or between complementary strands (interstrand), preventing strand separation necessary for transcription and replication; platinum compounds (cisplatin, carboplatin, oxaliplatin) preferentially form 1,2-intrastrand adducts at adjacent guanine residues, structurally distorting the double helix and triggering p53-mediated apoptosis. Antimetabolites structurally mimic endogenous nucleotides or cofactors and are incorporated into DNA or RNA or competitively inhibit biosynthetic enzymes: methotrexate inhibits dihydrofolate reductase (DHFR), depleting tetrahydrofolate necessary for thymidylate and purine synthesis; 5-fluorouracil is converted intracellularly to FdUMP, which covalently inhibits thymidylate synthase; cytarabine is phosphorylated to ara-CTP, incorporated into DNA, and terminates chain elongation. Anthracyclines (doxorubicin, daunorubicin, epirubicin) intercalate between DNA base pairs and inhibit topoisomerase II, causing double-strand breaks; they also generate reactive oxygen species through redox cycling that damage mitochondrial DNA in cardiomyocytes, producing the cumulative dose-dependent cardiotoxicity limiting their lifetime dose. Vinca alkaloids (vincristine, vinblastine, vinorelbine) bind beta-tubulin and prevent tubulin polymerization, preventing spindle formation and arresting cells in metaphase; taxanes (paclitaxel, docetaxel) bind polymerized tubulin and stabilize the spindle, preventing depolymerization and cell division—the inverse mechanism converging on the same lethal endpoint of mitotic arrest.</p>
    <p>Cytotoxic pharmacokinetics are characterized by narrow therapeutic windows, complex multi-compartment distribution, extensive tissue binding, and variable metabolic activation requirements that create substantial interpatient variability. Most cytotoxic agents are administered intravenously because oral bioavailability is erratic or low, though capecitabine (an oral prodrug of 5-FU), oral cyclophosphamide, and oral etoposide provide notable exceptions. Methotrexate distributes widely, with CNS penetration limited by P-glycoprotein at the blood-brain barrier (exploited by intrathecal administration for CNS prophylaxis in leukemia); renal clearance of unchanged methotrexate at high doses requires aggressive hydration and urine alkalinization (pH >7) to prevent precipitation in renal tubules, and leucovorin rescue must be available. Cisplatin is rapidly and extensively bound to plasma proteins and tissue DNA, with an initial half-life of 25–50 minutes for the reactive unbound form and a terminal half-life of days to weeks for bound platinum; ototoxicity and nephrotoxicity are dose-limiting, requiring aggressive IV hydration (1–2 L saline before and after administration), and total cumulative platinum dose must be tracked across regimens. Cyclophosphamide and ifosfamide are prodrugs activated by hepatic CYP2B6 and CYP3A4 to active nitrogen mustard metabolites and the urinary toxic metabolite acrolein; acrolein causes hemorrhagic cystitis prevented by vigorous IV hydration and the uroprotectant mesna (2-mercaptoethanesulfonic acid), which reacts with acrolein in urine to form a non-toxic thioether.</p>
    <p>Cytotoxic adverse effects represent the most severe drug toxicities in clinical medicine, arising from damage to the normal rapidly-dividing tissues that share the proliferative vulnerability of malignant cells: hematopoietic precursors (bone marrow suppression), GI epithelium (mucositis, nausea, vomiting, diarrhea), and hair follicles (alopecia). Myelosuppression—leukopenia, neutropenia, thrombocytopenia, and anemia—is the dose-limiting toxicity of most cytotoxic regimens; the nadir (lowest blood count) typically occurs 10–14 days after chemotherapy administration, and febrile neutropenia (fever >38.3°C with ANC <500 cells/mcL) is a medical emergency requiring prompt initiation of broad-spectrum empirical antibacterials after obtaining blood cultures. Colony-stimulating factors (filgrastim, pegfilgrastim) reduce the duration and severity of neutropenia and are indicated prophylactically when regimen-associated febrile neutropenia risk exceeds 20%. Chemotherapy-induced nausea and vomiting (CINV) is mechanistically driven by 5-HT3 receptor activation in the GI tract and CTZ (by cisplatin and anthracyclines, classified as highly emetogenic), substance P/neurokinin-1 receptor activation (late phase), and dopaminergic pathways; multimodal antiemetic prophylaxis combining ondansetron or palonosetron, dexamethasone, aprepitant (NK1 antagonist), and olanzapine provides superior CINV control compared to any single agent. Cumulative anthracycline cardiotoxicity—dilated cardiomyopathy and systolic dysfunction—is irreversible and dose-dependent, with lifetime cumulative dose limits of approximately 450–550 mg/m² for doxorubicin; baseline and periodic echocardiographic surveillance of left ventricular ejection fraction is mandatory.</p>
    <p>Cytotoxic nursing practice requires specialized competency in hazardous drug handling, patient safety, and anticipatory adverse effect management. Safe handling standards mandate PPE including double chemotherapy gloves, gowns, and face protection during preparation and administration; all cytotoxic agents are classified as hazardous drugs by NIOSH and must be prepared in certified laminar airflow hoods with dedicated negative-pressure rooms. The nurse must verify a five-point safety check before each administration: correct patient identity (two identifiers), correct drug, correct dose against BSA-calculated orders, correct route, and correct cycle day against the treatment plan. Extravasation of vesicant chemotherapy agents (doxorubicin, vincristine, paclitaxel, oxaliplatin) into tissue causes severe necrosis and must be prevented by use of central venous access for all vesicant administration; if extravasation occurs, administration must stop immediately, the needle aspirated, appropriate antidote applied (dexrazoxane IV for anthracycline extravasation, hyaluronidase for vinca alkaloids), the limb elevated and documented photographically, and oncology and plastic surgery consulted urgently. Educating patients about the expected time course of adverse effects—hair loss beginning 2–3 weeks after the first cycle, nadir neutropenia at 10–14 days, mucositis onset at 5–7 days—and evidence-based self-care strategies (oral cryotherapy during 5-FU infusion to reduce mucositis, neutropenic diet, fever reporting thresholds) is central to the oncology nursing role.</p>
  </div>

  {drugs.length === 0 && (
    <div class="alert alert-info mb-6">
      <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" class="stroke-current shrink-0 w-6 h-6"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M13 16h-1v-4h-1m1-4h.01M21 12a9 9 0 11-18 0 9 9 0 0118 0z"></path></svg>
      <span>No drugs are currently classified under this therapeutic class. Check back as more drug data is added.</span>
    </div>
  )}

  {drugs.length > 0 && (
    <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 xl:grid-cols-3 gap-4">
      {drugs.map((drug: any) => (
        <div class={`card card-compact bg-base-100 shadow border border-base-200 ${drug.ismp_high_alert ? 'border-l-4 border-l-error' : ''}`}>
          <div class="card-body">
            <div class="flex flex-wrap items-start gap-1 mb-1">
              <h2 class="card-title text-base font-semibold capitalize mr-auto">
                <a href={`${base}drugs/${drug.id}/`} class="hover:text-primary transition-colors">
                  {drug.generic_name}
                </a>
              </h2>
              {drug.prototype_for && <span class="badge badge-success badge-sm shrink-0">PROTOTYPE</span>}
              {drug.ismp_high_alert && <span class="badge badge-error badge-sm shrink-0">HIGH ALERT</span>}
              {drug.black_box_warnings && drug.black_box_warnings.length > 0 && <span class="badge badge-warning badge-sm shrink-0">BBW</span>}
            </div>
            <p class="text-xs text-base-content/60 mb-1">
              <span class="font-medium">{drug.drug_class}</span>
              {drug.subclass && <span> — {drug.subclass}</span>}
            </p>
            {drug.mechanism_summary && <p class="text-sm text-base-content/70 line-clamp-3">{drug.mechanism_summary}</p>}
            <div class="card-actions justify-end mt-2">
              <a href={`${base}drugs/${drug.id}/`} class="btn btn-xs btn-outline btn-primary">Profile</a>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      ))}
    </div>
  )}
</SchemaLayout>
